## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern: **Timeout enforcement** via `Thread.Abort`

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. The fix is **cooperative cancellation** with `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread` + `thread.Abort()` | `Task.Run` + `CancellationToken` | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OCE`, not `TAE` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed; cancellation is cooperative |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive the token to cooperate |

### Critical Pitfall: Cancellation Is Not Instant

The old code could forcibly kill the thread mid-execution. **Cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token.** Callers must update their lambdas:

```csharp
// ❌ Old usage — will NOT stop on timeout in .NET 8
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
        Process(item);  // never checks token
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ New usage — checks token at each checkpoint
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### If You Can't Modify `work` to Accept a Token

For truly uncooperative code (third-party libs, long native calls), **move it to a child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no safe in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET:

```csharp
// Last resort for uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Backward-Compatible Overload (Optional)

If you have many callers that don't need the token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
    // ⚠️ Warning: timeout will NOT interrupt work — it only
    // fires after work completes or if Task.Run checks the token.
}
```

> **This overload is a trap** — it compiles but the timeout only races against `work`; it cannot interrupt it. Add it only as a temporary bridge during migration, and log a warning when it's called.
